# Data Loading, Checking and Cleaning

## Load the data

The dataset used in this report is a subset of the [Atlas of Living Australia](https://www.ala.org.au/) (ALA) dataset, slightly modified for academic assignment purposes. It contains records of when and where the Swift Parrot has been observed. The dataset was imported into Tableau Public for visual analysis. First, the data file was downloaded from Moodle. It was then opened in Tableau Public by selecting File followed by Open. Once the dataset was loaded, visualizations were created in the worksheets.

## Irregularity 1: Mismatched Data Resource UID and Name

To check the consistency between dataResourceUid and dataResourceName, I created a visualization in Tableau to identify mismatched UID-name pairs. This showed that two records labelled as eBird Australia were linked to unexpected UIDs. One of these was assigned to dr2008, which refers to the ACT Wildlife Atlas. However, the ALA metadata indicates that this dataset was last updated in March 2016, while the record in my dataset was collected in 2019 (Atlas of Living Australia, 2019). This suggests that dr2008 was unlikely to be the correct source, so I relied on dataResourceName and corrected both records to dr2009, the correct UID for eBird Australia.

```{r}
#| results: asis

cat("
\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering

\\setlength{\\fboxsep}{4pt}
\\fbox{\\includegraphics[width=0.7\\textwidth]{figure/irregular-1.png}}

\\caption{Mismatch check for dataResourceName and dataResourceUid. The figure shows that eBird Australia was linked to multiple UIDs, indicating inconsistent resource identification.}

\\end{figure}
")
```

## Irregularity 2: Duplicate Records

According to the [Atlas of Living Australia](https://support.ala.org.au/support/solutions/articles/6000221758-how-does-the-ala-manage-duplicate-records-) (ALA, 2019), duplicate records may be uploaded and labelled as representative or associated. However, this dataset does not allow confirmation of whether repeated records represent true duplicate observations. To assess this issue, I created one field to classify observations as unique or duplicate after excluding recordID, and another to count duplicated rows by date. This showed that each year from 2018 to 2025 contained more than 100 duplicated rows, while records with null dates accounted for 463 duplicated rows. To improve analytical accuracy and support more reliable answers to the research questions, I removed recordID and deleted duplicate observations in R using the distinct() function.

```{r}
#| results: asis 

cat("
\\begin{figure}[htbp]
\\centering
\\includegraphics[width=0.7\\textwidth]{figure/irregular-2.png}
\\caption{Temporal pattern of repeated records based on comparison after excluding \\texttt{recordID}. The figure shows that the years 2018 to 2025 each contained more than 100 repeated rows, while records with missing date values accounted for 463 repeated rows. These repeated records were not assumed to be true duplicate observations.}
\\label{fig:duplicate-records}
\\end{figure}
")
```

