## Additional data preparation

To examine the quality and distribution of observationDate, I first created a bar chart in Tableau. This showed that some records were not recognised as valid dates and that a small number were associated with very early years. After checking these values, I found that some dates were stored in the yyyy-mm-dd format instead of the more common dd/mm/yyyy format, so I converted them first and then applied dmy() in R to standardize the entire field. The chart also showed that records before 1996 were sparse, while the data for 2026 covered only January, so I focused the later temporal analysis on the most recent complete 30-year period, from 1996 to 2025.

```{r}
#| results: asis 

cat(" 
\\begin{figure}[htbp] 
\\centering 
\\begin{minipage}[t]{0.8\\textwidth} \\centering \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figure/error-1.png} \\caption{Before date standardization, Tableau did not recognise 3,430 observations as valid dates, which appeared as unclassified values in the bar chart.} 
\\end{minipage} 
\\end{figure} 
")
```

Moreover, scientificName and vernacularName each contained only one unique value in the dataset. As these variables provided no additional analytical value, they were removed from the dataset.

```{r}
#| results: asis

cat(" 
\\begin{figure}[htbp] 
\\centering 
\\begin{minipage}[t]{0.75\\textwidth} \\centering \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figure/error-3.png} \\caption{Unique values in scientificName and vernacularName. Both variables had only one unique value and were removed.} 
\\end{minipage} 
\\end{figure} 
")
```

```{r}
library(readr)
library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(stringr)

ala <- read_csv("data/ALA_S12026PE1.csv")

ala_clean_resource <- ala %>%
  mutate(
    dataResourceUid = if_else(
      dataResourceName == "eBird Australia" & dataResourceUid != "dr2009",
      "dr2009",
      dataResourceUid
    )
  )

ala_clean_date <- ala_clean_resource %>%
  mutate(
    observationDate = if_else(
      str_detect(observationDate, "^\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}$"),
      str_replace(observationDate, "^(\\d{4})-(\\d{2})-(\\d{2})$", "\\3/\\2/\\1"),
      observationDate
    ),
    observationDate = dmy(observationDate)
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    observationDate = format(observationDate, "%d/%m/%Y")
  ) 

ala_clean_state <- ala_clean_date %>%
  mutate(
    stateProvince = case_when(
      decimalLongitude == 150.7 & decimalLatitude == -35.1 ~ "New South Wales",
      decimalLongitude == 150.8 & decimalLatitude == -35.2 ~ "New South Wales",
      recordID == "6a621dc2-f4a0-4e93-9b54-9520a650da33" ~ "Tasmania",
      TRUE ~ stateProvince
    )
  )

ala_dedup <- ala_clean_state %>% 
  select(-recordID, -scientificName, -vernacularName) %>% 
  distinct()

ala_1996_2025 <- ala_dedup %>%
  mutate(observationDate = dmy(observationDate)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(observationDate),
         year(observationDate) >= 1996,
         year(observationDate) <= 2025)
```

# Data Exploration and Presentation

## Question 1A: When were these birds observed over time?

I used Tableau to create a yearly line chart and a monthly bar chart based on Observation Date and record count. A line chart is appropriate for yearly observations because it highlights change over continuous time, while a bar chart is suitable for monthly counts because it supports comparison across discrete calendar months. The yearly chart showed that observations changed over time but generally increased in recent years, with clear peaks in 2019, 2021, and 2024. The monthly chart showed a strong seasonal pattern, with the highest counts in May, followed by August and June, and the main peak occurring between April and August. In contrast, February had the fewest records. Overall, the data suggests that Swift Parrot observations became more common in recent years and were concentrated in specific months.

```{r}
#| fig.cap: "Number of Swift Parrot observations by year from 1996 to 2025. Annual observations fluctuated over time but increased overall in recent years, with notable peaks in 2019, 2021, and 2024."
#| fig.align: center
#| out.width: "70%"

knitr::include_graphics("figure/q1a-year.png")
```

```{r}
#| fig.cap: "Monthly distribution of Swift Parrot observations from 1996 to 2025. Observation counts were highest in May, followed by August and June, with the main peak occurring between April and August."
#| fig.align: center
#| out.width: "70%"

knitr::include_graphics("figure/q1a-month.png")
```

## Question 1B: How have the number of observations from different data resources changed over time?

To identify the data resources with sufficient temporal coverage, I first created a stacked bar chart in Tableau and placed Observation Date at the year level on Columns, record count on Rows, and dataResourceName on colour. A stacked bar chart helps identify major contributing resources and their relative composition by year. This visualization showed that several resources were both active and supported by enough records for further analysis.

```{r}
#| fig.cap: "Annual composition of Swift Parrot observations by data resource from 1996 to 2025. The chart shows that a small number of data resources contributed most of the records across the study period."
#| fig.align: center
#| out.width: "80%"

knitr::include_graphics("figure/q1b-bar.png")
```

I filtered the six main resources identified in the stacked bar chart and changed the marks to lines in Tableau so their trends could be compared more clearly. In the earlier years, most records came from the *Victorian Biodiversity Atlas*, *New South Wales Bird Atlassers*, and *Tasmanian Natural Values Atlas*, but these sources were either inconsistent or stopped contributing after certain years. By contrast, *eBird Australia* became much more important over time, with clear peaks in 2019, 2021, and 2024, and more than 1,000 records in 2024. *NSW BioNet Atlas* was also active for much of the period, but its pattern was less stable, while *iNaturalist Australia* grew quickly after 2018 and overtook *NSW BioNet Atlas* in 2023 to become the second-largest source. Overall, the data shifted from being mainly supported by atlas-based sources in the earlier years to being dominated by *eBird Australia* in recent years, with *iNaturalist Australia* also becoming more important.

```{r}
#| fig.cap: "Number of Swift Parrot observations over time by the six major data resources from 1996 to 2025. Earlier records were mainly contributed by atlas-based sources, while recent records were increasingly dominated by eBird Australia, with iNaturalist Australia also becoming more important."
#| fig.align: center
#| out.width: "70%"

knitr::include_graphics("figure/q1b-line.png")
```

## Question 1C: In which Australian states and territories were these birds mainly spotted?

To answer this question, I created a filled map in Tableau using stateProvince, with record count shown by colour and labels. This made it easy to compare where Swift Parrot observations were mainly recorded across Australia. The map showed that most observations were concentrated in Victoria, New South Wales, and Tasmania, while the other states and territories had much lower counts. Overall, the birds were mainly spotted in south-eastern Australia.

```{r}
#| fig.cap: "Swift Parrot observations by Australian state and territory, 1996-2025. Darker shading indicates higher observation counts, and labels show the number of records in each region. Most observations were concentrated in Victoria, New South Wales, and Tasmania."
#| fig.align: center
#| out.width: "90%"

knitr::include_graphics("figure/q1c-map.png")
```

## Question 2: Can the data resources reveal seasonal migration?

Based on the visualizations in Questions 1A-1C, I think the data resources show some signs of seasonal migration, but not strongly enough to confirm it. These visualizations were not detailed enough to directly examine seasonal migration, because they did not link month, state, and data resource in the same view. With more targeted visual analysis, such as comparing monthly patterns across both states and data resources, the dataset may provide stronger evidence of seasonal movement. At the same time, the dataset also has limitations, including uncertainty in some records and incomplete coverage across years and data resources. These issues make it harder to determine seasonal migration confidently. Therefore, I could not confidently identify whether it is possible to determine this from 1A-1C.

